==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Say
<hw>Say</hw> <pr>(s⟦amac⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Aphetic form of
<ets>assay</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Trial by sample; assay;
sample; specimen; smack.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If those principal works of God . . . be but certain tastes and
<qex>says</qex>, as it were, of that final benefit.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy tongue some <qex>say</qex> of breeding breathes.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Tried quality; temper; proof.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He found a sword of better <qex>say</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Essay; trial; attempt.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To give a say at</b></col>, <cd>to attempt.</cd>
<rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Say</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Say
<hw>Say</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To try; to assay.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Say</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Say
<hw>Say</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>saie</ets>, F.
<ets>saie</ets>, fr. L. <ets>saga</ets>, equiv. to <ets>sagum</ets>,
<ets>sagus</ets>, a coarse woolen mantle; cf. Gr. <grk>sa`gos</grk>. See
<er>Sagum</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A kind of silk or satin.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou <qex>say</qex>, thou serge, nay, thou buckram lord!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A delicate kind of serge, or woolen cloth.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His garment neither was of silk nor <qex>say</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Say</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Say
<hw>Say</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Said</conjf> <pr>(s⟦ecr⟧d)</pr>, contracted from
<xex>sayed</xex>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Saying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>seggen</ets>,
<ets>seyen</ets>, <ets>siggen</ets>, <ets>sayen</ets>, <ets>sayn</ets>,
AS. <ets>secgan</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>seggian</ets>, D.
<ets>zeggen</ets>, LG. <ets>seggen</ets>, OHG. <ets>sag⟦emac⟧n</ets>, G.
<ets>sagen</ets>, Icel. <ets>segja</ets>, Sw. <ets>s⟦aum⟧ga</ets>, Dan.
<ets>sige</ets>, Lith. <ets>sakyti</ets>; cf. OL. <ets>insece</ets>
tell, relate, Gr. <grk>'e`nnepe</grk> (for <grk>'en-sepe</grk>),
<grk>'e`spete</grk>. Cf. <er>Saga</er>, <er>Saw</er> a saying.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To utter or express in words; to tell; to speak; to
declare; <as>as, he <ex>said</ex> many wise things</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Arise, and <qex>say</qex> how thou camest here.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To repeat; to rehearse; to recite; to pronounce;
<as>as, to <ex>say</ex> a lesson</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of my instruction hast thou nothing bated⟦br⟧
In what thou hadst to <qex>say</qex>?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>After which shall be <qex>said</qex> or sung the following
hymn.</q> <rj><qau>Bk. of Com. Prayer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To announce as a decision or opinion; to state
positively; to assert; hence, to form an opinion upon; to be sure about;
to be determined in mind as to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But what it is, hard is to <qex>say</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To mention or suggest as an estimate, hypothesis, or
approximation; hence, to suppose; -- in the imperative, followed
sometimes by the subjunctive; <as>as, he had, <ex>say</ex> fifty
thousand dollars; the fox had run, <ex>say</ex> ten
miles</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Say</qex>, for nonpayment that the debt should double,⟦br⟧
Is twenty hundred kisses such a trouble?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>It is said</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>They
say</b></col></mcol>, <cd>it is commonly reported; it is rumored; people
assert or maintain.</cd> -- <col><b>That is to say</b></col>, <cd>that
is; in other words; otherwise.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Say</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Say
<hw>Say</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To speak; to express an opinion; to
make answer; to reply.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You have <qex>said</qex>; but whether wisely or no, let the forest
judge.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To this argument we shall soon have <qex>said</qex>; for what
concerns it us to hear a husband divulge his household privacies?</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Say</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: Say
<hw>Say</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Say</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>;
cf. <er>Saw</er> a saying.]</ety> <def>A speech; something said; an
expression of opinion; a current story; a maxim or proverb.</def>
<mark>[Archaic or Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He no sooner said out his <qex>say</qex>, but up rises a cunning
snap.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That strange palmer's boding <qex>say</qex>,⟦br⟧
That fell so ominous and drear⟦br⟧
Full on the object of his fear.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sayer</ent>⟦br⟧
